<ab><lb n="1"/> <w lemma="ὁ">ἡ</w> <w lemma="σορός">σορός</w> <w lemma="εἰμί">ἐστιν</w> <w lemma="καί">κὲ</w> <w lemma="ὁ">ὁ</w> <w lemma="τόπος">τό<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">πος</supplied></w>    <gap reason="lost" extent="6" unit="character" extentmax="7"/>  <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Διονύσιος">Διονυ<lb n="3" break="no"/>σίου</name>  <lb n="4"/><g ref="#leaf"/>  <num value="4">δ</num>  <g ref="#leaf"/>  <lb n="5"/><persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Διογενιανός">Διογε<lb n="6" break="no"/>νια<lb n="7" break="no"/>νοῦ</name></persName></persName>  </ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation" sample="complete" org="uniform">
            <p>The sarcophagus and the plot <gap reason="lost" extent="6" unit="character" extentmax="7"/> belong to Dionysios, fourth of the name from Diogenianos.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary" sample="complete" org="uniform">
            <p>It is not certain that we have the owner's full name, since either a short Greek name or an abbreviated Roman praenomen and nomen, e.g. <foreign xml:lang="grc">Μ(άρκου) Αὐρηλ(ίου)</foreign>, could have stood at the end of l.1. If the name was wholly Greek he presumably died before the Edict of Caracalla in A.D. 212; if he had Roman citizenship it may well have been after that, but his genealogy suggests (although it does not prove) that he was the first Roman citizen in the family.</p>
         </div>
